==Epidemiology==
Embryonal teratomas most commonly occur in the sacrococcygeal region: [[sacrococcygeal teratoma]] is the single most common tumor found in newly born humans.

Of teratomas on the skull sutures, approximately 50% are found in or adjacent to the [[orbit (anatomy)|orbit]].<ref>{{EMedicine|oph|620|Orbital dermoid cyst}}</ref>   '''Limbal dermoid''' is a '''[[choristoma]]''', not a teratoma.

Teratoma qualifies as a [[rare disease]], but is not extremely rare.  Sacrococcygeal teratoma alone is diagnosed at birth in one out of 40,000 humans.  Given the current human population and birth-rate, this equals five per day or 1800 per year.  Add to that number sacrococcygeal teratomas diagnosed later in life, and teratomas in other locales, and the [[Incidence (epidemiology)|incidence]] approaches ten thousand new diagnoses of teratoma per year.

Teratomas also occur, rarely, in other species.<ref name="pmid18622858">{{cite journal
| author = López RM, Múrcia DB
